[Student "S"]
{You have a totally square 13 points. Still, you don't want to ignore a 4-card \S suit so you respond 1\S. Partner rebids 2\D. What do you say next? 

You COULD bid 3\C, FSF, to find out if partner has a \C stopper but that would be pointless. You already know of an 8-card \H fit so you say 4\H.}

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "4"]
[Dealer "W"]
[Vulnerable "All"]
[Deal "W:743.K2.KJT8.AQ96 A985.JT85.Q54.J8 KQJ62.963.A6.K54 T.AQ74.9732.T732"]
[Declarer "E"]
[Contract "4S"]
[Result ""]
[Auction "W"]
1D pass 1S pass 2C pass 2H pass 2S pass 4S all pass pass pass
[BCFlags "1f"]
[RotationNote "Board 4, chOption: E, chBasis: N, basisKind:Declarer, nOption:1, nBasis: 0, nRot: 1, useStandardVul: true"]
[BoardVersionToken "d4b59169a8967174d1cd5c65c17bb60d763bed57561eb6f93ecc95ec1503762a"]
[Category "Bidding Conventions"]
[Difficulty "intermediate"]
[SkillPath "bidding_conventions/fourth_suit_forcing"]
[Student "S"]
{With both 4-card minors you open 1\D. Partner responds 1\S.  

You cannot support \Ss with only 3 of them. Instead you bid 2\C. Partner says 2\H.  

This is FSF, asking you to further describe your hand, and you have a problem. You do have a \H stopper so you COULD bid 2NT. You also have 3 \Ss so you COULD bid 2\S. Either way might turn out best, but that \HK looks pretty lonesome so you choose 2\S and partner raises to 4\S.}

